                            <comment id="110647" author="rstoya05-aop" created="Fri, 12 Dec 2014 08:29:47 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Or is it perhaps that if we are given an HttpClient, i.e. the &lt;tt&gt;HttpComponentsClientHttpRequestFactory(HttpClient httpClient)&lt;/tt&gt; constructor is used, then none of the other properties in the factory  (connectTimeout, socketTimeout) apply and therefore we should not change the RequestContext? &lt;tt&gt;InternalHttpClient&lt;/tt&gt; is an internal class so I&apos;m not sure we can rely on it i any way.&lt;/p&gt;
</comment>
                            <comment id="110673" author="ractive" created="Mon, 15 Dec 2014 02:17:10 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;You&apos;re right. &lt;tt&gt;InternalHttpClient&lt;/tt&gt; is a package private class so you can&apos;t use it.&lt;br/&gt;
You really could argue that if an HttpClient is given to the &lt;tt&gt;HttpComponentsClientHttpRequestFactory&lt;/tt&gt; (e.g. in the c&apos;tor), it&apos;s supposed to be configured and the factory should not change the RequestContext anymore. Not sure how much client code will break with such a change though...&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="110866" author="snicoll" created="Mon, 22 Dec 2014 02:47:12 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;The factory allows to tune very specific details and it&apos;s true that it now overrides a bunch of unrelated customizations. We have a similar problem with &lt;tt&gt;HttpComponentsHttpInvokerRequestExecutor&lt;/tt&gt; actually. The best of both worlds would be to &lt;b&gt;merge&lt;/b&gt; the things that we want to customize over the things that were set by a configured HttpClient but unfortunately I don&apos;t see how we could do that with the current API. Maybe the best solution would be to opt-in for that behaviour with a boolean flag or separate that in two different factories. We still have users that have 4.3 on their classpath but pass a deprecated &lt;tt&gt;HttpClient&lt;/tt&gt; instance as an argument so I am not sure how that would work if we choose this to be the default.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Another idea would be to pass the &lt;b&gt;default&lt;/b&gt; &lt;tt&gt;RequestConfig&lt;/tt&gt; alongside the &lt;tt&gt;HttpClient&lt;/tt&gt; instance and we would use that to merge our settings with the ones coming from those defaults. The problem with this approach is that it&apos;s not &quot;XML-friendly&quot; and it feels weird to set both the &lt;tt&gt;HttpClient&lt;/tt&gt; and the &lt;tt&gt;RequestConfig&lt;/tt&gt; since the latter can be set in the former. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I have also reported that problem on the HttpComponents &lt;a href=&quot;http://marc.info/?l=httpclient-users&amp;amp;m=141925754526751&amp;amp;w=2&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;mailing list&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Thoughts?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
