                            <comment id="110930" author="snicoll" created="Tue, 23 Dec 2014 08:50:09 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I have actually pushed &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/snicoll/spring-framework/commit/9b399623ead96b0a4b386f248d320ccc0850aaa6&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;a proposal in my branch&lt;/a&gt; - We&apos;re still figuring out if we could manage that in a better way.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="110979" author="snicoll" created="Mon, 29 Dec 2014 00:46:30 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;We&apos;re now creating a custom &lt;tt&gt;RequestConfig&lt;/tt&gt; only if customizations are applied on the factory. Otherwise, the defaults of the http client are applied.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="111019" author="pkrasko" created="Tue, 30 Dec 2014 17:41:30 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Stephane - thanks for looking at this issue.  It actually hit me 2 days ago and I ended up creating a default request config on a subclass of HttpComponentsClientHttpRequestFactory, ironically almost identical to what you posted above.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I needed to alter the CookieSpec on the RequestConfig to ignore all cookies.&lt;br/&gt;
The RequestConfig has about 14 configurable properties, where only 3 of them are actually configurable in the new HttpComponentsClientHttpRequestFactory.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The good news is if you have the defaults setup properly on the HttpClient then you can totally forget about RequestConfigs on a per request level, and you wouldn&apos;t need to call setConnectTimeout, setConnectionRequestTimeout, and setReadTimeout.  My guess is this will be the 90% use case.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;However, if one would want to alter the behavior per request the 3 exposed methods don&apos;t really do much justice compared to the 14 configurable properties on the RequestConfig.  Would it make sense to have a protected method to access the RequestConfig with the URI and HttpMethod as arguments?  That would really give a consumer full flexibility.  It&apos;s just a thought I had while I was reading all the source the other night, and was actually going to file a ticket when I saw 4.1.4 was released and it addressed the very thing I was working on.&lt;/p&gt;


</comment>
                            <comment id="111038" author="snicoll" created="Wed, 31 Dec 2014 06:44:27 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Hi Phil - we actually discussed this before the fix was applied. The problem is that &lt;tt&gt;RequestConfig&lt;/tt&gt; can be set on an &lt;tt&gt;HttpClient&lt;/tt&gt; but there is no way you can retrieve it so the only way really is to offer a way to pass a &lt;tt&gt;HttpClient&lt;/tt&gt; and a &lt;tt&gt;RequestConfig&lt;/tt&gt; which would be &lt;em&gt;weird&lt;/em&gt;. Specifying a &lt;tt&gt;RequestConfig&lt;/tt&gt; extra parameter would be as equally weird to me since you&apos;d get the default of the client, the default of the factory and then the actual instance the request would be using....&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We&apos;ve reported that problem to &lt;a href=&quot;http://mail-archives.apache.org/mod_mbox/hc-httpclient-users/201412.mbox/%3CCANH3%2BntNs%2BgN%3DDDcWPM6vrzgN-dkREWnQrHPUB%3DkOcCLiJNHbQ%40mail.gmail.com%3E&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;the mailing list&lt;/a&gt; and HC 4.4 will have a public API for that. This actually reminds me I forgot to create the issue to take this new API into account. I&apos;ve created &lt;a href=&quot;https://jira.spring.io/browse/SPR-12583&quot; title=&quot;Merge default request config with local customizations&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;SPR-12583&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;SPR-12583&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt;. In that case our local &lt;tt&gt;RequestConfig&lt;/tt&gt; will be a merge between the &lt;tt&gt;RequestConfig&lt;/tt&gt; of the &lt;tt&gt;HttpClient&lt;/tt&gt; and any local customizations. You&apos;ll need Http Components 4.4. for this to  work.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Does that make sense? Thanks for the feedback!&lt;/p&gt;

</comment>
                            <comment id="111042" author="pkrasko" created="Wed, 31 Dec 2014 07:51:38 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Yes, that makes perfect sense.&lt;br/&gt;
In 4.3 you would be forced to supply both the default RequestConfig, and the HttpClient in the constructor, which is less than ideal.  It&apos;s nice to know that 4.4 will fix the issue by providing an API.  Thanks again.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
